data.content:
Yes — use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType<T>()`. It combines the type check and cast, and gives a clear failure message instead of an `InvalidCastException`:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();
    var result = factory.Create("email");

    var handler = Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
}
```

The generic overload (MSTest 3.x+) returns the cast object so you can keep asserting on it. If the type doesn't match, you get a descriptive failure like *"Expected type: EmailHandler. Actual type: SmsHandler."*
